    <tax:treatment obkms_id="0582903d-7ec9-4f2f-ae0c-077dfc2147b3" obkms_process="TRUE">
      <tax:nomenclature obkms_id="cbc39d45-3923-4d7d-b7eb-341e85c2d073" obkms_process="TRUE">
        <tax:name obkms_id="259992c6-4b7e-402b-8b33-dced455f218c" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Castniidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Castnia</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>strandi</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank><dwc:scientificNameAuthorship>(Houlbert, 1917)</dwc:scientificNameAuthorship></tax:xmldata>strandi (Houlbert, 1917)</tax:name>
      </tax:nomenclature>
      <tax:ref_group>
        <tax:p><tax:name obkms_id="8fb3b3ac-c7aa-4533-86f3-06bdbdaa0389" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Castniidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Castnia</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>strandi</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank><dwc:scientificNameAuthorship>Houlbert, 1917</dwc:scientificNameAuthorship></tax:xmldata>Castnia strandiHoulbert, 1917</tax:name>:Études de Lépidoptérologie comparée13: 75–76. (fig. 16).</tax:p>
      </tax:ref_group>
      <tax:div type="materials_examined" obkms_id="38514752-e927-4ccb-be71-19ee1e1500a9" obkms_process="TRUE">
        <tax:p>Type material. GL believes he has found the specimen used byStrand (1913: 12, pl. 6c, fig. [1], ascronius [sic]) for his illustration of<tax:name obkms_id="81a3d9f1-0e29-46ad-8a58-9cfadedb779a" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Castniidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Haemonides</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>cronis</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>C. cronis</tax:name> in MNHU; it is a female, as is the illustration. Embrik Strand (1876–1947) was working in MNHU in 1913 so he must have seen this specimen in Staudinger’s collection deposited there; it is therefore highly likely that this is a syntype of<tax:name obkms_id="87416e87-2fbb-43c4-9ee6-269917bd7aa1" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Castniidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Castnia</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>strandi</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>strandi</tax:name>. It has no data other than “Coll. Sommer”.</tax:p>
        <tax:p>Type locality. In Strand’s (1913: 12) entry for<tax:name obkms_id="6fecfea4-a8b1-4124-a748-772e8414c185" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Castniidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Haemonides</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>cronida</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>cronida</tax:name>, which follows his entry for<tax:name obkms_id="779143d9-c9ea-490e-9fdb-366909db976d" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Castniidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Haemonides</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>cronis</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>cronis</tax:name>, he writes “Both occurr [sic] inGuiana ”. As he believed he was merely providing an example of<tax:name obkms_id="49e77cf2-a2fc-4dea-8784-91bc44eb584d" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Castniidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Haemonides</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>cronis</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>cronis</tax:name> this cannot be taken as an indication of thetype locality.Houlbert (1917) writes “sa patrie serait laGuyane, mais aucune indication précise n’a été donée sur ce point”; therefore thetype locality is unknown with both authors merely stating that the taxon is found inFrench Guiana, although Strand may have meantGuyana.</tax:p>
        <tax:p>Taxonomic status. The name is a junior primary homonym of<tax:name obkms_id="85f703b2-5108-4889-8683-cf34bc4850ba" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Castniidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Castnia</dwc:Genus><dwcranks:subgenus>Gazera</dwcranks:subgenus><dwc:Species>strandi</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank><dwc:scientificNameAuthorship>Niepelt, 1914</dwc:scientificNameAuthorship></tax:xmldata>Castnia (Gazera)strandi Niepelt, 1914</tax:name> and was replaced by<tax:name obkms_id="8d41bcab-b039-450a-85d4-d55d345dc129" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Castniidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Haemonides</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>candida</dwc:Species><dwc:Subspecies>houlbertina</dwc:Subspecies><dwc:taxonRank>subspecies</dwc:taxonRank><dwc:scientificNameAuthorship>Lamas, 1995</dwc:scientificNameAuthorship></tax:xmldata>H. candida houlbertinaLamas, 1995</tax:name>. It was originally described as a species and treated as a subspecies of<tax:name obkms_id="9a1f0483-95b7-491b-9c6b-8d5a3cfc1bd4" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Castniidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Haemonides</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>cronis</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>cronis</tax:name> byMiller (1995);Lamas (1995) then treated it as a subspecies of<tax:name obkms_id="21c6a650-601d-4da6-9be0-5e55f66b0be7" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Castniidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Haemonides</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>candida</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>H. candida</tax:name>, to which Strand’s (1913) figure bears little resemblance. However, it is here considered to be a junior subjective synonym of nominotypical<tax:name obkms_id="cd662255-74bd-4dd1-b59d-d97a947d5d8e" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Castniidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Haemonides</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>cronis</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>H. cronis</tax:name>.</tax:p>
      </tax:div>
      <tax:div type="distribution" obkms_id="9214e116-ac3a-4d2b-9c5f-c101e04eb6e9" obkms_process="TRUE">
        <tax:p>Distribution. Not relevant,<tax:name obkms_id="f5009f4f-6e89-4608-bca5-a144ee5d5050" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Castniidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Haemonides</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>cronis</dwc:Species><dwc:Subspecies>cronis</dwc:Subspecies><dwc:taxonRank>subspecies</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>seecronis</tax:name> above.</tax:p>
      </tax:div>
      <tax:div type="discussion" obkms_id="5fdabe13-2b6d-4a5f-9cff-35dc5fefb6bb" obkms_process="TRUE">
        <tax:p>Discussion. This is a name given byHoulbert (1917) for Strand’s<tax:name obkms_id="56546a1a-4e73-4a12-bb69-d20630652d6a" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Castniidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Castnia</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>cronis</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>Castnia cronis</tax:name>.Strand (1913) was merely listing the known<tax:name obkms_id="c1e96d18-7d6b-427c-8ae0-64802e96614f" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Castniidae</dwc:Family><dwc:taxonRank>family</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>Castniidae</tax:name> in Seitz’s magnum opus and provided a brief description and figure for Cramer’s<tax:name obkms_id="e9a31a1f-c64c-4fa0-92c2-7e27bb8768dd" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Papilionidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Papilio</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>cronis</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>Papilio cronis</tax:name>.Houlbert (1917) decided that Strand’s illustration represented a different species from Cramer’s<tax:name obkms_id="3354423e-c87d-44cb-8257-29344bbcfe84" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Papilionidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Papilio</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>cronis</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>cronis</tax:name> and proposed the name<tax:name obkms_id="d1fb745e-f9a5-4fa0-ab62-32814cbb9a22" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Castniidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Castnia</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>strandi</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>strandi</tax:name> for the new species.Lamas (1995) then proposed the replacement name<tax:name obkms_id="4bf77fe4-53c9-4deb-8a7c-04e9feae2819" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Castniidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Haemonides</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>candida</dwc:Species><dwc:Subspecies>houlbertina</dwc:Subspecies><dwc:taxonRank>subspecies</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>houlbertina</tax:name> for the homonymic<tax:name obkms_id="ec7006e1-62df-4292-9fef-136e00bc1634" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Castniidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Castnia</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>strandi</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>strandi</tax:name> and moved it to the species<tax:name obkms_id="ebad8141-9f8c-4aff-a8b6-7af4f1cde461" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Castniidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Haemonides</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>candida</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>H. candida</tax:name>. At the time that Houlbert was writing specimens of<tax:name obkms_id="b78e4e41-15be-4d22-b545-be29a7392999" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Castniidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Haemonides</dwc:Genus><dwc:taxonRank>genus</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>Haemonides</tax:name> were very rare in collections and it seems from his treatise that he had never seen an actual specimen of<tax:name obkms_id="b8e24fdd-060c-4fc5-9ce4-382b5b689605" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Papilionidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Papilio</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>cronis</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>H. cronis</tax:name> but was only working from illustrations in past works. He could also have been confused by the fact that Cramer’stype of<tax:name obkms_id="e205f538-b53c-4a6e-9b23-5f9b7f788fed" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Papilionidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Papilio</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>cronis</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>cronis</tax:name> was an artefact which included the forewings of a<tax:name obkms_id="3d5cbbcf-3fb1-428e-a251-fd1d196b553a" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Papilionidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Papilio</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>cronis</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>cronis</tax:name> male and Strand’s figure was a female. Much more material of all taxa has been available for this work, which shows that<tax:name obkms_id="99640bdc-dc4a-4909-8e0e-01ffef71628c" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Castniidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Castnia</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>strandi</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>strandi</tax:name> is within the range of variation of nominotypical<tax:name obkms_id="141edfa3-9325-46d7-b65f-8af1dbe73e71" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Papilionidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Papilio</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>cronis</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>H. cronis</tax:name>.</tax:p>
      </tax:div>
    </tax:treatment>
